         <div type="edition" xml:lang="grc" xml:space="preserve">

<ab><lb n="1"/> <w lemma="ζάω">Ζῶσιν</w> <lb n="2"/> <w lemma="ὁ">ὁ</w> <w lemma="πλάτας">πλάτας</w> <w lemma="εἰμί">ἐστιν</w> <lb n="3"/> <persName type="attested"><name nymRef="#Τιβέριος"><expan><abbr>Τι</abbr><ex>βερίου</ex></expan></name> <name nymRef="#Κλαύδιος"><expan><abbr>Κλ</abbr><ex>αυδίου</ex></expan></name> <name nymRef="#Ἀχιλλεύς">Ἀχιλλέ<lb n="4" break="no"/>ως</name></persName>  </ab>
</div>
         <div type="translation">
            <p>They are living. The platform belongs to Ti(berius) Cl(audius) Achilleus ?[ . . . </p>
         </div>
         <div type="commentary">
            <p>It is not clear from the record whether the text finished at this point, but the plural used in line 1 suggests that at least two persons were named as buried in the tomb concerned.</p>
            <p>There is almost certainly a Tib. Claudius Achilleus named in <ref type="inscription" n="1534" target="120524.xml"/> (=MAMA 559), where he is the grandfather of the wife of one of those to be buried in what seems to be quite an extensive tomb. It is possible that the Achilleus of <ref type="inscription" n="1578" target="120714.xml"/>  (=MAMA 570) was another (or became one on enfranchisement by his master, Ti. Cl. Attalos).</p>
         </div>
         <div type="bibliography" n="none">
            <p>Unpublished.</p>
         </div>
